/*
FINALLY RUNNING BELOW 60FPS on my desktop machine!  =]


Okay, there's still a lot to do, but this gets the proof-of-concept out of the way.

First, the checklist of what works;
* "Recursive" ray tracing.
* Reflection and refraction of nested objects. This only works if the interior
  objects' indices of refraction are specified relative to their parent. A sphere
  of ior 1.8 inside a 1.5 is specified with an ior of 1.8/1.5.
* "Barf-o-morphism" I want to just keep a list of objects, each of which knows its
  type. You just write the intersection function for an object type (and, 
  eventually, provide texturing info) and you don't have to think about anything else.
* Fresnel reflection. Glass objects don't _just_ refract. Some of the light that
  hits the glass surface is reflected. It's a complicated interaction that involves
  the polarization of light and it's not worth getting into here. Frankly, I can't
  even say I barely understand it. I'm operating on faith here.
* Perlin noise. Only currently used for warping the mandelbrot texture. I may use it
  to create some "proper" textures like wood, etc. Maybe
* Visible light sources. It's fake, but it's not too bad. It depends upon the angle
  between the cast ray and the direction to the center of the light source, which
  means its size is constant in screenspace and gives it a very wonky behavior as
  it passes in front of the camera. I don't know if I'll try to fix this.
* Soft shadows. This is expensive as hell. It's easier to see with only one light
  source or without the messed up mandelwarp. I may eliminate this to go to just one
  light and try to do actual real-time caustics. That's probabaly the next project,
  and I'll have to finish it before Kerbal Space Program 2 comes out.
* Depth-of-field. Only those things at the camera's focal length are in sharp focus.

3.1
* Incorporated my shader debugger into the ray tracer. I need to do some more thought
  about how it prints (eliminate "normal", "color", "distance"?) But it's there and it
  already helped me eliminate a bug where I was recursing too deeply.

3.1.1
* Planes with UV mapping. 
* UV mapping supports chromakey.

GLSL has no recursion. "Recursive" ray-tracers generally work by replacing a ray,
when it hits a refractive surface, with one ray that goes through the object surface
and one that reflects off of it. These two rays are computed by a self call to a 
trace() function... which you can't do in glsl.

Instead, I just have a worklist of unprocessed rays. Each ray knows how much of the
final color it contributes. For example, if a ray passes through a filter, the ray that
comes out the other side knows that whatever it hits in the end, only a fraction of
the surface's color will be used for the pixel color. Each time a ray hits a filter
of any kind, new rays are generated with more and more attenuation.

I have no idea how to explain this properly. It's too late at night for that. Hit me
up in the comments and I'll try to make sense of it. In the meantime, enjoy the todo
